text: {'text': 'A cosy pub when the sun goes down and zichar stall in the day. Ordered fried hokkien prawn mee, moonlight horfan and a salted egg diced chicken rice for takeaway dinner. Food was surprisingly good and tasty!  Friendly staff! Will definitely be back!', 'languageCode': 'en'}

name: places/ChIJKcZTGl4R2jERQkZ0iJGnLm0/reviews/ChdDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnSUNQZzhfeWlnRRAB
text: {'text': 'Very good charcoal steamboat. Soup rich in la la stock. Ingredients fresh and not not a lot of variety but cheap and decent enough for a good meal. The fish is very fresh and the wagyu beef is very tender. At $10 per plate, it’s a steal. Their friend chicken wings is also value for money. $8 for 10 pieces. Vegetables free and unlimited. Ebiko prawn part at $8 is also a must to order. You can actually see bits of prawn in the paste.', 'languageCode': 'en'}

name: places/ChIJKcZTGl4R2jERQkZ0iJGnLm0/reviews/ChdDSUhNMG9nS0VJQ0FnSUNSeEtUdnZRRRAB
text:
{'text': 'Googled for restaurants in Jurong East and this place popped up! However, it has nothing to do with chocolate haha. The food is more of a western-Chinese fusion.

• Garlic Mala Fries ($12.90)- STRONGLY RECOMMEND! Huge plate with lots of seasoning.

• Seafood Aglio Olio ($16.90)- generous with the garlic! They have other versions with crab stick, mushroom and crab meat.

• Flambé Beef Cubes ($15.90)- with black pepper sauce and can taste the wokhei.

• Wild Truffle Mushroom Soup ($7.90)- can’t really discern the truffle but it’s full of mushroom bits. Accompanied with garlic bread topped with fresh garlic.', 'languageCode': 'en'}
